Live Demo: The Prompt Comparison1. The "Lazy" PromptGoal: Show what happens when a user doesn't use a framework.Interaction: Copy the messy Excel data and paste it below this simple line.Prompt:"Clean this data for me and fix the dates."[PASTE EXCEL DATA HERE]Expected Result: The AI will likely fix the dates and maybe some text, but it will probably give you back a wall of text or a simple list that is hard to copy back into Excel. It might miss the logic in the 'Comments' column entirely.2. The "COSTAR" Framework PromptGoal: Show a deterministic, professional, and actionable output.Interaction: Explain each part of the COSTAR acronym as you type/paste it.Prompt:(C) Context: I am an Associate Data Scientist working with the ETF Operations team. I have a raw, messy export of daily trades that contains inconsistent formatting.(O) Objective: I need you to clean this data so it can be re-imported into our master reconciliation sheet.Standardize all dates to 'DD-MMM-YYYY' (e.g., 01-Dec-2023).Ensure all Asset Names are in UPPERCASE.Clean the Price column to be numeric only (remove $, £, and change commas to periods).(S) Style: Financial Analyst / Data Auditor.(T) Tone: Objective and professional.(A) Audience: My Operations Manager who needs to see a clean status report.(R) Response: Provide two outputs:A Markdown table containing the fully cleaned data.A separate "High Priority Issues" list for any trades where the status is 'ERROR' or 'Pending'.[DATA TO PROCESS]:[PASTE EXCEL DATA HERE]Expected Result: You will get a perfectly formatted table that is easy to copy back into Excel, plus a structured bulleted list highlighting the risks—ready for an email to a manager.
